The JeuneS3 programme is a partnership framework aligned with the Dutch SRHR policy with a focus on young people (especially girls) and key populations in francophone fragile countries or areas in Africa. The partnership works in Cameroon, Central African Republic, the Democratic Republic of Congo and Benin.

The project will target to offer service to all populace of all gender and ages,male and female,boys and girls including the mostly vulnerable groups like persons with disabilities,elderly,refugees,returnees and internally displaced persons.The project will to collect and analyse data so that it can be disaggregated as much as possible by gender, age and any other social construct that inform programme decision-making and implementation.

Young people aged 10-24 years, with special focus on girls aged 10-14 yrs and key populations in francophone fragile countries or areas in Africa: Cameroon (Extreme North and East) , Central African Republic (CAR) and the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) (Eastern part: North-and South Kivu) and Benin (North).

Cordaid promotes more effective, responsive and inclusive security and justice provision through its security and justice programmes. Cordaid has pioneered an innovative approach to tackling the aforementioned challenges through applying a results-based financing (RBF) model to security and justice provision. The approach is characterized by using the train & equip elements of standard security and justice sector reform incentives to focus on accountability and constructive relations between state duty-bearers and citizens. Informed by successful utilization of RBF in the health sector, Cordaid first introduced an RBF approach to security and justice (S&J) in 2011 in DR Congo. Subsequently, two projects were rolled-out: Restoring the Contract (2012-17) in Burundi and DRC, and CISPE (2017-  ) in DRC. 
In the course of implementing these initiatives, Cordaid has refined the RBF for S&J model, adapting to the needs of beneficiaries and feedback from external evaluations and donors, evolving toward an â€œRBF 2.0â€ that is fit-for-purpose in the existing context. Adaptations integrated into the latest iteration of RBF for S&J include separation of quantitative and qualitative (i.e. process-oriented) indicators to clarify targets for beneficiaries, inclusion of lower-level governance actors and civil society organizations in RBF, and splitting the community verification process into an end-user verification and a broader community questionnaire (to reach people who did not use RBF-associated services). Most of these changes are related to better include local community representatives (women, youth, local business associations, etc.) in the RBF process and promote accountability. 
The proven success of Cordaid RBF for S&J programming in Burundi and DRC calls for adaptation and scaling-out of this approach globally. To do so, assessment is needed of how Cordaid interventions in DRC impact the local political economy, that is, power relations between local political actors, formal and informal, who have a central role in security and justice provision, and between citizens (especially women, youth and marginalized groups) and power-holders.

Engendered peace - WPS: CEPO (Grace John Kenyi, South Sudan) and MFFPS (Catherine Mabobori, Burundi) were able to address the 33rd Pre-Summit Civil Society Consultative Meeting on Gender Mainstreaming in the African Union (GIMAC) held on 3rd and 4th February 2019, and highlight the important peace-building role of women in protection of civilian sites and IDP camps in South Sudan as well as the need to include displaced women in peace building processes. GIMAC 33 bore the theme â€œTowards Gender-Responsive Durable Solutions to Forced Displacementâ€. In preparation for SP partner WIPC and Cordaid partners in Burundi, South Sudan, DRC and Uganda were consulted to identify key issues that could be amplified or advocated for during GIMAC based on the work and evidence of these organisations or networks. Partners were invited to speak during the different thematic panels. These issues were discussed and reflected in the final GIMAC recommendations which called for support for displaced womenâ€™s to occupy leadership positions in decision-making in IDP and refugee camps. The outcome document also called for the participation of women in the inter-Burundian dialogue and the need for its revival. The AU Women, Gender and Development Directorate received these recommendations to feed into the processes leading up to the AU Heads of State summit.

Security and access to Justice: Two visits to NYC with partners and colleagues which involved 2 partners and 1 local staff of Cordaid from DRC and CAR to share information and recommendations regarding the extension of the mandate of MONUSCO and MINUSCA to permanent representations, NYC-based NGOs and specific UN country teams.

Inclusive Health services: Cordaid and local CSOs in DRC contributed to the design of the national strategy for Universal Health Coverage in DRC.
